    <title type="text">Imagery of Archaeological Site Looting</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/cultural-heritage-center/syria-cultural-heritage-initiative/imagery-archaeological-site-looting">Imagery
      of Archaeological Site Looting</a><br />United States State Department Bureau of
      Educational and Cultural Affairs <br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><img
      alt="http://eca.state.gov/sites/all/themes/custom/eca_bureau/logo.png" class="decoded"
      src="http://eca.state.gov/sites/all/themes/custom/eca_bureau/logo.png" />
      </blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">These satellite images document the scale of destruction that looters continue to
      inflict on archaeological heritage sites during the ongoing conflict in Syria. Looting at
      archaeological sites destroys irreplaceable evidence of life and society in the ancient world.
      In the case of Syria, this evidence has helped researchers understand important historical
      developments such as the beginnings of agriculture and cities, the rise and fall of empires,
      and the development and spread of Judaism, Christianity and Islam. Syria’s rich archaeological
      corpus includes several ancient settlements on the <a
      href="http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/SY/" target="_blank">UNESCO World Heritage List
      and Tentative List</a> and many others that help us understand the mosaic of human
      history.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><i>Dura Europos</i></span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">This unique Classical-period site, founded in the 3rd century BC and occupied
      until the 3rd century AD, demonstrates the diversity of the ancient Middle East. One of the
      world’s earliest churches was discovered here, as was one of the oldest preserved synagogues
      and numerous temples devoted to polytheistic deities. This important site of approximately 150
      acres (60 hectares) is now covered by looters’ pits.</span><br /><table
      align="center" border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" style="width:
      700px;"><tbody><tr><td><div align="center"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/dura_28june12_labels_1.jpg" target="_blank"><img
      src="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/dura_28june12_labels.jpg" height="200" width="300"
      /></a></span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">28 June 2012
      </span></div></td><td><div align="center"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/dura_02april14_details_2.jpg"
      target="_blank"><img src="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/dura_02april14_details.jpg"
      height="200" width="300" /></a></span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">02 April 2014
      </span></div></td></tr><tr><td><div
      align="center"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/dura_28june12_base_1.jpg" target="_blank">Larger
      view (Hi-Res)</a></span></div></td><td><div
      align="center"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/dura_02april14_base_1.jpg" target="_blank">Larger
      view
      (Hi-Res)</a></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><i>Mari</i></span><br /><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">Mari was an important city in the Early and Middle Bronze Ages
      (ca. 3000-1600 BC). Excavations have recovered cuneiform archives as well as the remains of the
      famous “palace of Zimri-lim,” which was destroyed by Hammurabi of Babylon in the mid-18th
      century BC. Looters here have sunk several pits in the area of Zimri-lim’s palace and at other
      places in the city center.</span><br /><table align="center" border="0"
      cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" style="width:
      700px;"><tbody><tr><td><div align="center"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/mari_07sept12_labels_3.jpg" target="_blank"><img
      src="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/mari_07sept12_labels.jpg" height="200" width="300"
      /></a></span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">07 September
      2012 </span></div></td><td><div align="center"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/mari_25mar14_labelsdetail_3.jpg"
      target="_blank"><img
      src="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/mari_25mar14_labelsdetail.jpg" height="200" width="300"
      /></a></span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">25 March 2014
      </span></div></td></tr><tr><td><div
      align="center"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/mari_07sept12_base_0.jpg" target="_blank">Larger
      view (Hi-Res)</a></span></div></td><td><div
      align="center"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/mari_25mar14_base_1.jpg" target="_blank">Larger view
      (Hi-Res)</a></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><i>Tell Sheikh Hamad</i></span><br
      /><span style="font-size: x-small;">In the late 2nd millennium BC (beginning around
      1350 BC), this site served as the regional capital of Assyria’s western provinces; in the 1st
      millennium BC, it was an important administrative center in the Assyrian empire. Looting here
      has focused on the citadel area, as well as parts of the lower town.</span><br
      /><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" style="width:
      700px;"><tbody><tr><td><div align="center"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/sheikhhamad_1mar11_labels_0.jpg"
      target="_blank"><img
      src="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/sheikhhamad_1mar11_labels.jpg" height="200" width="300"
      /></a></span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">01 March 2011
      </span></div></td><td><div align="center"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/sheikhhamad_3mar14_labels_0.jpg"
      target="_blank"><img
      src="http://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/sheikhhamad_3mar14_labels.jpg" height="200" width="300"
      /></a></span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">03 March 2014
      </span></div></td></tr><tr><td><div
      align="center"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="https://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/sheikhhamad_1mar11_base.jpg" target="_blank">Larger
      view (Hi-Res)</a></span></div></td><td><div
      align="center"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="https://eca.state.gov/files/bureau/sheikhhamad_3mar14_base.jpg" target="_blank">Larger
      view
      (Hi-Res)</a></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table><br
      /></blockquote>]]></content>
